VALUES
(43, 9, 2, 42, 13, 2, 2, NULL, 'Understanding Sin and Suffering', 'Both passages emphasize the question of sin in relation to suffering. In John 9:2, the disciples inquire about the cause of a man''s blindness, while in Luke 13:2, Jesus addresses assumptions about the sinfulness of those who suffer. This connection highlights a common theme of questioning the relationship between sin and suffering.', 'theme', 0.412, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 2, 43, 9, 34, 34, NULL, 'Connection of Sin and Blindness', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of being ''born in sins.'' The disciples inquire about the cause of blindness related to sin, while the response to the healed man suggests he is judged for being ''altogether born in sins.''', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 2, 2, 20, 5, 5, 'who did sin', 'Sin and Its Consequences', 'This connection highlights the theme of sin and its repercussions across generations. Both passages address the concept of iniquity, with John 9:2 questioning the source of sin related to suffering, while Exodus 20:5 discusses the consequences of sin affecting descendants.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 2, 44, 28, 4, 4, 'who did sin', 'Sin and Suffering Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of sin and its consequences. In John 9:2, the disciples question whether sin caused blindness, while in Acts 28:4, the barbarians assume the man''s suffering is due to his past sins.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 2, 40, 16, 14, 14, NULL, 'Perceptions of Sin and Identity', 'This connection highlights how both passages reflect the disciples'' inquiries into identity and causation. In John 9:2, the question of sin relates to the man''s blindness, while in Matthew 16:14, the question of Jesus'' identity involves prophetic figures, suggesting a search for understanding in both contexts.', 'theme', 0.286, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 2, 40, 23, 7, 7, NULL, 'Discipleship and Authority', 'This connection highlights the theme of authority in discipleship. In John 9:2, the disciples seek understanding from Jesus, while in Matthew 23:7, the emphasis is on being called ''Rabbi,'' indicating a desire for recognition and authority.', 'theme', 0.272, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 3, 43, 11, 4, 4, NULL, 'Connection of God''s Glory', 'Both passages emphasize that circumstances, such as sickness or blindness, serve a purpose for the glory of God. In each case, the events are framed as opportunities for God''s works to be revealed.', 'theme', 0.552, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 3, 21, 9, 1, 2, 'the works of God should be made manifest', 'Divine Sovereignty Over Human Affairs', 'Both passages emphasize that human circumstances, whether righteous or wicked, are ultimately under God''s control. John 9:3 highlights God''s purpose in suffering, while Ecclesiastes 9:1-2 reflects on the equal fate of all people, suggesting that God''s works are manifest in both the good and the bad.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 3, 43, 11, 40, 40, 'the works of God should be made manifest', 'Manifestation of God''s Glory', 'This connection highlights the theme of God''s works being revealed. In both passages, the emphasis is on witnessing the glory of God through belief and divine action.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 3, 18, 2, 3, 6, NULL, 'Suffering and Divine Purpose', 'Both passages emphasize the idea of suffering without direct cause. In John 9:3, the man''s condition serves to manifest God''s works, while in Job 2:3-6, Job''s suffering is allowed by God to test his integrity, highlighting a divine purpose behind affliction.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 3, 40, 11, 5, 5, 'the works of God should be made manifest', 'Healing and Manifestation of God', 'This connection highlights the theme of healing and divine works. Both passages emphasize the miraculous acts of Jesus, showcasing the manifestation of God''s power through healing the blind and other afflicted individuals.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 3, 18, 42, 7, 7, 'the works of God should be made manifest', 'Suffering and Divine Purpose', 'This connection highlights the theme of suffering as a means for God''s works to be revealed. Both passages emphasize that the afflictions faced by individuals are not necessarily due to personal sin, but rather serve a greater divine purpose.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 3, 44, 4, 21, 21, 'the works of God should be made manifest', 'Manifestation of God''s Works', 'This connection highlights the theme of God''s works being made manifest. In John 9:3, the purpose of the man''s condition is to reveal God''s works, while Acts 4:21 shows people glorifying God for what was done, indicating a similar manifestation of divine action.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 4, 43, 12, 35, 35, NULL, 'Light and Darkness Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the contrast between light and darkness, highlighting the urgency of acting while light is present. The mention of ''night'' in John 9:4 and ''darkness'' in John 12:35 underscores the necessity of working in the light before it is too late.', 'theme', 0.825, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 4, 49, 5, 16, 16, 'while it is day', 'Work and Time in Scripture', 'Both passages emphasize the urgency of action in the face of evil. John 9:4 speaks of working while it is day, while Ephesians 5:16 urges redeeming the time due to the evil days. This connection highlights the need for diligence in doing good.', 'theme', 0.685, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 4, 43, 4, 34, 34, 'the works of him that sent me', 'Connection of Jesus'' Work', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of doing the work of God. John 9:4 mentions ''the works of him that sent me,'' while John 4:34 refers to ''the will of him that sent me.'' This connection highlights a shared theme of fulfilling divine purpose.', 'theme', 0.657, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 4, 21, 9, 10, 10, 'work the works of him that sent me', 'Work and Opportunity in Life', 'This connection highlights the urgency of performing work while one has the opportunity. Both passages emphasize the importance of action during life, as the ability to work ceases after death.', 'theme', 0.6359999999999999, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 4, 48, 6, 10, 10, 'work the works of him that sent me', 'Call to Action in Faith', 'This connection highlights the urgency of doing good while there is opportunity. Both passages emphasize the importance of working for others, especially within the faith community.', 'theme', 0.573, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 4, 51, 4, 5, 5, 'while it is day', 'Work and Time Management', 'This connection highlights the urgency of action in both passages. John 9:4 emphasizes the need to work while there is time, paralleling Colossians 4:5''s call to redeem the time wisely.', 'theme', 0.503, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 4, 23, 38, 18, 19, 'work the works of him that sent me', 'Work and Praise Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of the living in performing actions and praising God. John 9:4 highlights the urgency of working while there is time, while Isaiah 38:18-19 underscores that the living are the ones who can praise God and share His truth.', 'theme', 0.412, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 5, 43, 8, 12, 12, 'I am the light of the world', 'Connection of Light in John', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus as the light of the world, highlighting the importance of following Him to avoid darkness. This connection reinforces the theme of spiritual illumination and guidance.', 'theme', 0.45399999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 5, 43, 12, 46, 46, 'light of the world', 'Light of the World Connection', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus as the light of the world, highlighting the importance of belief in Him to avoid darkness. This connection underscores the theme of spiritual illumination and guidance provided by Jesus.', 'theme', 0.419, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 5, 44, 13, 47, 47, 'light of the world', 'Light and Salvation Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of light as a guiding force. John 9:5 presents Jesus as the light of the world, while Acts 13:47 refers to being a light for the Gentiles, indicating a broader mission of salvation.', 'theme', 0.40499999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 5, 23, 42, 6, 7, 'light of the world', 'Light and Blindness Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of light bringing sight and liberation. John 9:5 declares Jesus as the light, while Isaiah 42:6-7 speaks of a light for the Gentiles that opens blind eyes.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 5, 44, 26, 18, 18, 'light of the world', 'Light and Darkness Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of light overcoming darkness. In John 9:5, Jesus identifies himself as the light of the world, while Acts 26:18 speaks of turning people from darkness to light, emphasizing the transformative power of faith.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 5, 49, 5, 14, 14, 'light of the world', 'Light of the World Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of light. John 9:5 presents Jesus as the light of the world, while Ephesians 5:14 speaks of Christ giving light to those who arise from the dead.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 5, 66, 21, 23, 23, 'the light of the world', 'Light in Scripture', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of light, with John 9:5 declaring Jesus as ''the light of the world'' and Revelation 21:23 describing the Lamb as ''the light thereof.'' This connection highlights the continuity of the theme of divine illumination throughout the biblical narrative.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 6, 41, 7, 33, 33, 'spit', 'Healing through Spittle', 'Both passages emphasize the act of spitting as part of the healing process. In each instance, Jesus uses spittle to facilitate restoration, highlighting a physical connection to healing.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 6, 41, 8, 23, 23, NULL, 'Healing of the Blind', 'Both passages emphasize the act of spitting as part of the healing process for blind individuals. This connection highlights a shared method used by Jesus to restore sight, showcasing his miraculous power.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 6, 66, 3, 18, 18, 'anointed the eyes of the blind man', 'Healing and Spiritual Insight', 'Both passages emphasize the act of anointing the eyes, linking physical sight with spiritual understanding. The blind man''s healing in John symbolizes the deeper need for spiritual vision addressed in Revelation.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 7, 23, 35, 5, 5, NULL, 'Healing of the Blind', 'Both passages emphasize the opening of the eyes of the blind, highlighting a theme of miraculous healing. John 9:7 describes a specific instance of this healing, while Isaiah 35:5 prophesies the future restoration of sight.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 7, 43, 9, 11, 11, 'Go, wash in the pool of Siloam', 'Connection of Healing and Obedience', 'Both passages emphasize the act of washing in the pool of Siloam as a crucial step in the healing process. The SOURCE verse describes the instruction to wash, while the TARGET passage recounts the man''s obedience to that instruction, leading to his sight being restored.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 7, 43, 11, 37, 37, NULL, 'Healing and Sight', 'This connection highlights the theme of healing and restoration. Both passages emphasize the miraculous ability of Jesus to bring sight and life, linking the healing of the blind man to the raising of Lazarus.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 7, 19, 146, 8, 8, NULL, 'Healing of the Blind', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine healing, as both passages address the opening of the eyes of the blind. John 9:7 describes a specific act of healing, while Psalms 146:8 speaks generally of the Lord''s power to open the eyes of the blind.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 7, 23, 8, 6, 6, NULL, 'Connection of Shiloah and Siloam', 'This connection highlights the significance of the waters of Shiloah in Isaiah, which symbolizes spiritual nourishment, paralleling the healing act at the pool of Siloam in John. Both passages emphasize the importance of water as a means of restoration and insight.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 7, 44, 26, 18, 18, 'came seeing', 'Healing and Spiritual Insight', 'This connection highlights the theme of opening eyes, both physically in John 9:7 and spiritually in Acts 26:18. Both passages emphasize a transformation from darkness to light, illustrating the broader concept of enlightenment and healing.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 7, 2, 4, 11, 11, NULL, 'Healing and Divine Authority', 'Both passages emphasize God''s power over physical conditions, such as sight and speech. John 9:7 illustrates a specific healing act, while Exodus 4:11 underscores God''s sovereignty in creating and controlling these abilities.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 8, 9, 2, 8, 8, 'he that sat and begged', 'Connection of Poverty and Restoration', 'Both passages emphasize the elevation of the poor and the blind. John 9:8 refers to a man who was blind and now seen, while 1 Samuel 2:8 speaks of lifting the beggar from the dunghill. This connection highlights God''s transformative power in restoring dignity.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 8, 9, 21, 11, 11, 'Is not this he', 'Recognition of Identity', 'This connection highlights the theme of recognition in both passages, where individuals question the identity of someone they have seen before. In John 9:8, the neighbors recognize the formerly blind man, while in 1 Samuel 21:11, Achish''s servants recognize David as a well-known figure. Both instances emphasize how public perception shapes identity.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 8, 41, 10, 46, 46, 'that sat and begged', 'Blindness and Begging Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of blindness and begging. In John 9:8, the man who was blind is recognized by his neighbors, while in Mark 10:46, blind Bartimeus is described as sitting by the highway side begging.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 8, 42, 16, 20, 22, 'that sat and begged', 'Connection of Begging and Recognition', 'This connection highlights the theme of begging and the recognition of individuals in need. Both passages feature a beggar, with the neighbors in John questioning the identity of the formerly blind man, paralleling the recognition of Lazarus at the rich man''s gate.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 8, 42, 18, 35, 35, 'that sat and begged', 'Blindness and Begging Connection', 'Both passages emphasize a blind man who is begging. This connection highlights the social condition of blindness and the act of begging in the context of healing.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 8, 44, 3, 2, 11, 'Is not this he that sat and begged?', 'Healing and Recognition', 'Both passages emphasize the transformation of individuals who were previously known for their disabilities. In each case, the community recognizes them after their miraculous healings, leading to wonder and amazement.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 8, 8, 1, 19, 19, 'Is not this he', 'Recognition of Identity', 'Both passages emphasize the community''s reaction to an individual''s changed status. In John 9:8, the neighbors question the identity of the formerly blind man, while in Ruth 1:19, the townspeople inquire about Naomi''s identity upon her return.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 10, 21, 11, 5, 5, NULL, 'Understanding God''s Works', 'This connection highlights the mystery of divine actions. Both passages emphasize the inability of humans to fully comprehend the workings of God, whether in miraculous events or natural processes.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 10, 41, 4, 27, 27, NULL, 'Growth and Understanding of Miracles', 'This connection highlights the theme of understanding miraculous events. In John 9:10, the question of how the man''s eyes were opened reflects a curiosity about the process of miracles, similar to Mark 4:27, which discusses the mysterious growth of seeds, emphasizing the unknown aspects of divine workings.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 10, 43, 3, 9, 9, NULL, 'Questions of Understanding', 'Both passages emphasize a question posed to Jesus regarding understanding miraculous events. The inquiries reflect a theme of seeking clarity about divine actions.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 10, 43, 9, 15, 15, 'How were thine eyes opened?', 'Inquiry about Healing', 'Both passages emphasize the inquiry of the Pharisees regarding the healing of the blind man. The repeated question, ''How were thine eyes opened?'' in the first passage connects directly to their subsequent inquiry in the second passage about how he received his sight.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 10, 46, 15, 35, 35, 'How were thine eyes opened?', 'Questions of Transformation', 'This connection highlights the theme of transformation through questioning. Both passages emphasize inquiries about significant changes: the opening of eyes in John and the resurrection of the dead in Corinthians.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 11, 43, 9, 6, 7, 'made clay, and anointed mine eyes', 'Healing of the Blind Man', 'Both passages emphasize the act of Jesus making clay and anointing the blind man''s eyes. They describe the same miracle, highlighting the process of healing through washing in the pool of Siloam.', 'parallel', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 11, 43, 9, 27, 27, 'A man that is called Jesus', 'Discipleship and Witness', 'This connection highlights the theme of witnessing Jesus'' actions. In both passages, the man emphasizes his experience with Jesus, suggesting a growing recognition of his role as a disciple.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 11, 24, 36, 17, 17, 'said unto me, Go to the pool of Siloam, and wash', 'Connection of Divine Instruction', 'This connection highlights the theme of receiving guidance from God. In both passages, individuals are instructed to act based on divine words, leading to significant outcomes: sight in John and the writing of God''s message in Jeremiah.', 'theme', 0.258, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 12, 2, 2, 18, 20, 'Where is he?', 'Inquiry About a Missing Man', 'Both passages emphasize a question about the whereabouts of a man. In John 9:12, the inquiry is directed towards the healed blind man, while in Exodus 2:20, Reuel asks about the Egyptian who helped his daughters.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 12, 43, 5, 11, 13, 'I know not', 'Connection of Healing and Identity', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of healing and the uncertainty of the healed individuals regarding the identity of Jesus. In each case, the healed person does not know who healed them, highlighting a common experience of miraculous intervention without recognition of the healer.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 12, 43, 7, 11, 11, 'Where is he?', 'Inquiry About Jesus'' Location', 'Both passages emphasize the question, ''Where is he?'' which reflects the ongoing search for Jesus during significant events. This connection highlights the curiosity and confusion surrounding his whereabouts.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 13, 43, 8, 3, 8, 'brought to the Pharisees', 'Connection of Judgment and Mercy', 'Both passages emphasize the act of bringing individuals before authority figures, highlighting themes of judgment and mercy. In John 9:13, the blind man is brought to the Pharisees, while in John 8:3-8, the woman caught in adultery is presented to Jesus for judgment.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 13, 43, 11, 46, 47, 'the Pharisees', 'Miracles and Pharisaic Response', 'Both passages emphasize the involvement of the Pharisees in response to Jesus'' miracles. In John 9:13, the healed man is brought to the Pharisees, while in John 11:46-47, they gather to discuss Jesus'' miraculous works.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 13, 43, 11, 57, 57, 'him that aforetime was blind', 'Connection of Blindness and Authority', 'This connection highlights the ongoing conflict between Jesus and the religious authorities. In both passages, the actions of the Pharisees reflect their desire to control and investigate those who have experienced miraculous events, such as the healing of the blind man.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 13, 43, 12, 42, 42, NULL, 'Fear of Pharisees', 'This connection highlights the influence of the Pharisees on belief and confession. In both passages, the actions of the Pharisees create a barrier for individuals, whether it is bringing the blind man to them or causing rulers to hide their belief.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 13, 43, 12, 19, 19, 'the Pharisees', 'Pharisees'' Response to Jesus', 'This connection highlights the Pharisees'' growing concern over Jesus'' influence. In both passages, the Pharisees are depicted as reacting to the impact of Jesus'' miracles and teachings, particularly regarding the formerly blind man.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 14, 43, 5, 9, 9, NULL, 'Sabbath Healing Miracles', 'Both passages emphasize the significance of the sabbath in relation to miraculous healings performed by Jesus. The mention of the sabbath in both verses highlights a thematic connection regarding the nature of work and healing on this day.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 14, 40, 12, 1, 14, 'sabbath day', 'Sabbath Healing and Law', 'Both passages emphasize actions taken by Jesus on the sabbath, highlighting conflicts with the Pharisees regarding what is lawful. They illustrate the theme of mercy over strict adherence to the law, as Jesus performs healings and allows his disciples to eat.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 14, 42, 13, 10, 17, 'sabbath day', 'Sabbath Healing Miracles', 'Both passages emphasize healing on the sabbath, showcasing Jesus'' authority to perform miracles despite the established rules. The healing of the blind man in John and the woman with a spirit of infirmity in Luke both occur on the sabbath, highlighting the theme of compassion over legalism.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 14, 42, 6, 1, 11, 'sabbath day', 'Sabbath Healing and Controversy', 'Both passages emphasize actions taken by Jesus on the sabbath that provoke controversy with the Pharisees. In John 9:14, Jesus heals a man by making clay, while in Luke 6:1-11, he defends his disciples'' actions and heals a man with a withered hand, highlighting the tension between sabbath laws and doing good.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 14, 43, 5, 16, 16, NULL, 'Sabbath Controversy in John', 'Both passages emphasize actions taken on the sabbath day, highlighting the conflict between Jesus and the Jews regarding sabbath observance. This connection illustrates the tension surrounding Jesus'' healing activities on this holy day.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 15, 43, 9, 10, 11, 'put clay upon mine eyes', 'Healing of the Blind Man', 'Both passages emphasize the act of Jesus making clay and the subsequent washing that leads to the man''s sight being restored. This connection highlights the process of healing as described in both verses.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 15, 43, 9, 26, 27, NULL, 'Questioning the Miracle', 'Both passages emphasize the Pharisees'' persistent questioning of the man who received sight. The repeated inquiry about how his eyes were opened highlights their skepticism and the man''s frustration with their disbelief.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 16, 43, 7, 43, 43, 'there was a division among them', 'Division Among People', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of division among people regarding Jesus. In John 9:16, the division arises from differing opinions about Jesus'' actions on the Sabbath, while John 7:43 highlights a similar division among the people about him.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 16, 43, 10, 19, 19, 'there was a division among them', 'Division Among the Jews', 'Both passages emphasize the division among the Jews regarding Jesus'' actions and teachings. The first passage highlights the disagreement among the Pharisees about Jesus'' miracles, while the second passage notes a similar division due to his sayings.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 16, 40, 12, 2, 2, NULL, 'Sabbath Controversy Among Pharisees', 'Both passages emphasize the Pharisees'' criticism of actions deemed unlawful on the Sabbath. In John 9:16, they question the legitimacy of Jesus due to Sabbath violations, while in Matthew 12:2, they accuse His disciples of similar wrongdoing.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 16, 42, 13, 31, 33, 'This man is not of God', 'Pharisees and Jesus'' Authority', 'Both passages emphasize the opposition from the Pharisees towards Jesus. In John, they question His authority due to Sabbath violations, while in Luke, they warn Him of Herod''s threat, reflecting their ongoing conflict with His ministry.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 16, 44, 14, 4, 4, 'there was a division among them', 'Division Among Groups', 'This connection highlights the theme of division among groups regarding belief and authority. Both passages emphasize how differing opinions lead to conflict and division within communities.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 17, 43, 4, 19, 19, 'He is a prophet', 'Recognition of Prophetic Identity', 'This connection highlights the recognition of Jesus as a prophet in both passages. The blind man and the Samaritan woman both affirm Jesus'' prophetic identity based on their personal experiences.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 17, 43, 6, 14, 14, 'He is a prophet', 'Recognition of Jesus as Prophet', 'This connection highlights the acknowledgment of Jesus as a prophet in both passages. In John 9:17, the blind man identifies Jesus as a prophet, while in John 6:14, the crowd recognizes Him as ''that prophet'' who is to come.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 17, 44, 3, 22, 26, 'He is a prophet', 'Connection of Prophetic Identity', 'This connection highlights the recognition of Jesus as a prophet in John 9:17 and the prophetic role foretold in Acts 3:22-26. Both passages emphasize the importance of listening to the prophet raised by God.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 17, 40, 21, 11, 11, 'He is a prophet', 'Connection of Prophetic Identity', 'This connection highlights the recognition of Jesus as a prophet in both passages. In John 9:17, the blind man identifies Jesus as a prophet, while in Matthew 21:11, the multitude refers to Him as ''Jesus the prophet.''', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 9, 17, 42, 24, 19, 19, 'He is a prophet', 'Connection of Prophetic Identity', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' identity as a prophet. In John 9:17, the blind man acknowledges Jesus as a prophet, while in Luke 24:19, Jesus is described as a prophet mighty in deed and word.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
